CSS Properties and Values
CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is used to control the layout and appearance of web pages. Here are some basic CSS properties and values:

CSS Properties
1. color: Specifies the color of the text.
Example: color: red; (sets the text color to red)
2. background-color: Specifies the background color of the element.
Example: background-color: #f2f2f2; (sets the background color to a light gray)
3. font-size: Specifies the font size of the text.
Example: font-size: 20px; (sets the font size to 20 pixels)

CSS Values
1. Color Names: You can use color names like red, blue, green, etc.
Example: color: blue; (sets the text color to blue)
2. Hexadecimal Colors: You can use hexadecimal codes like #FF0000, #0000FF, etc.
Example: background-color: #FF0000; (sets the background color to red)
3. Length Units: You can use length units like px, em, rem, etc.
Example: font-size: 2em; (sets the font size to 2 times the parent element's font size)

HTML and CSS Code Example
HTML Code

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>CSS Properties and Values</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Welcome to CSS</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
  <div class="box">This is a box with a background color.</div>
  <div class="red-text">This text is red.</div>
  <div class="large-text">This text is large.</div>
</body>
</html>


CSS Code (in style.css file)

body {
  font-size: 20px;
  color: #333;
}

h1 {
  color: blue;
}

p {
  font-size: 1.5em;
}

.box {
  background-color: #f2f2f2;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

.red-text {
  color: red;
}

.large-text {
  font-size: 30px;
}


Real-time Examples
1. Changing Text Color: color: green; can be used to change the text color to green.
2. Setting Background Color: background-color: #000; can be used to set the background color to black.
3. Increasing Font Size: font-size: 24px; can be used to increase the font size to 24 pixels.

Questions and Answers
Q1: What is the purpose of the color property in CSS?
A1: The color property is used to specify the color of the text.

Q2: What is the difference between px and em units in CSS?
A2: px is an absolute unit that represents pixels, while em is a relative unit that represents the font size of the parent element.

Q3: How can you set the background color of an element to red using hexadecimal color code?
A3: You can use background-color: #FF0000; to set the background color to red.

Q4: What is the purpose of the font-size property in CSS?
A4: The font-size property is used to specify the size of the font.

Q5: Can you use color names like red, blue, etc. in CSS?
A5: Yes, you can use color names like red, blue, etc. in CSS to specify colors.